nities. Prioritise arrangements that ensure financiers\u2019 answerability to local actors. 3,4,7,8 ROAM Phase 3: Validation of results and recommendations 17. Ensure inclusive, transparent validation processes (consistent with Recommendations 5\u201310), such that outputs reflect the visions, priorities and knowledge of rights-holders and key stakeholders, including of Indigenous peoples and local communities, with FPIC. All 18. Ensure final ROAM outputs identify FLR initiatives that can uphold human rights and enable effective and equitable governance. If not done earlier (e.g. Recommendations 11 and 15) refine identified and prioritised initiatives as needed and provide guidance on governance issues that will need to be addressed for equitable, effective implementation. All 19. Adopt and roll-out an action plan for ROAM outputs through inclusive, coordinated processes. Include diverse and innovative solutions, including approaches defined and led by Indigenous peoples and local communities, with FPIC. Be clear about scale and build in ongoing safeguards and resources. 1,4,5, 6,8 20. Enable longer-term and participatory monitoring, learning and adaptation of FLR plans and strategies, including through devolved processes, and the application, where relevant, of the Restoration Barometer, with additional indicators related to governance. 1,3,5 xi Acknowledgements This publication was developed through a collaboration between the IUCN Commission on Environmental, Economic and Social Policy (CEESP), the Centre for Society and Governance \u2013 Human Rights in Conservation Team (known as the Global Programme on Governance and Rights (GPGR) at the time the publication was developed) and the IUCN Forest and Grassland Team (known as the Forest Conservation Programme (FCP) at the time the publication was developed). The views expressed are not necessarily those of any collaborating partner. The co-authors greatly appreciate the many people who contributed to this publication. Invaluable insights were shared by all interviewees. Inputs, guidance and/or coordination support were contributed by many CEESP, GPGR and FCP colleagues, including (with reference to titles at the time of publication development and in alphabetical order: Li Jia (formerly IUCN Forest Landscape Restoration Coordinator for the Asia region), James McBreen (Senior Programme Officer, IUCN Forest Landscape Restoration), Alain Ndoli (Senior Programme Officer, Forest Landscape Restoration, IUCN Rwanda), Carole Saint- Laurent (Deputy-Director, IUCN FCP), Jenny Springer (Director, IUCN GPGR) and Kristen Walker (Chair, IUCN CEESP). Edmund Barrow and Daniella Schweizer provided thoughtful and in-depth peer review. Lianuary Nurdin supported translation for research in Indonesia. Copy-editing was done by Diwata Hunziker. The NRGF framework and graphics are from Springer et al. (2021). James McBreen, Alain Ndoli and Robert Wild, along with co-authors Benjamin Brown, Emmanuel Nuesiri and Gretchen Walters, contributed text boxes that deepen the analysis. Our sincere thanks to all. The primary lens for analysis in this publication is the IUCN Natural Resource Governance Framework (NRGF). Several of the publication co-authors are NRGF Working Group members. This publication is among the first analyses of this type using the NRGF. In this sense, it is an NRGF pilot analysis.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "23c57535-e264-480e-8634-84c422be1cba": {"__data__": {"id_": "23c57535-e264-480e-8634-84c422be1cba", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/economic-assessment-abandoned-lost-and-otherwise-discarded-fishing-gear", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_